  "1": "The strength of our nation resides in the physical integrity of the labor force. The industrial machine is a demanding master that requires every component to function with absolute precision and vigor. We believe that the workplace is a temple of productivity where only the most robust and capable individuals find their place. Our current policy prioritizes the recruitment of the able-bodied candidate because the demands of the modern factory floor allow no room for the infirm or the physically compromised. When we look at the assembly line, we see a chain that is only as strong as its weakest link. For this reason, we discourage the hiring of those whose bodies or minds do not meet the rigorous standards of physical perfection. A worker with a missing limb, a clouded eye, or a slow mind is not merely a tragedy; such an individual is a liability to the safety of others and a drain on the efficiency of the enterprise. It is a matter of practical economics and public safety. We maintain that the responsibility for the care of the broken belongs to the family or the charitable institution, not the corporate balance sheet. The factory operates on the principle of maximum output, and such output is only possible when every worker possesses the full range of human motion and sensory perception. We value the sturdy citizen who stands tall and works without the need for modification or special consideration. To introduce those with functional limitations into this environment is to court disaster. The noise of the machinery is too loud for the hard of hearing; the pace of the belt is too fast for the slow of foot; the complexity of the gears is too great for the simple of mind. We protect our progress by ensuring that every man on the payroll is a specimen of health and vitality. Our recruitment centers are instructed to screen for any sign of biological failure. We do not apologize for this standard. We believe that the prosperity of the whole depends on the strength of the parts. The hiring of the robust is the only path to a stable and profitable future. Those who cannot contribute through standard physical labor are encouraged to find solace in quiet reflection away from the gears of industry, for the workshop is a place for the swift, the strong, and the whole.",
