Infrastructure: Based on Section 4, early crypto-malware primarily utilized monolithic binaries where the miner (e.g., cpuminer) was bundled directly with a dropper. Communication followed a direct client-to-pool architecture using the Stratum protocol without encryption. Persistence was achieved through simple registry modifications (HKCU/Software/Microsoft/Windows/CurrentVersion/Run).
Stealth: Evasion was rudimentary, relying almost exclusively on commercial packers (UPX, Themida) to bypass static signature-based detection. Resource management was non-existent; the miner would utilize 100% CPU, leading to rapid user discovery.

### Modern Malware Infrastructure and Evasion (2016-Present)
Infrastructure: Modern iterations employ modular, multi-stage delivery. Payloads are often fileless, residing in memory or WMI repositories. They utilize mining proxies to aggregate traffic, obfuscating the final destination (pool) and circumventing IP-based blacklisting. Lateral movement is integrated via exploits like EternalBlue.
