  "Method": "Past/Legacy DDoS Methods: The Era of Volumetric Brute Force. In the early stages of election-related cyber threats, the primary methodology revolved around 'Volumetric Flooding' and the exploitation of fundamental flaws in the TCP/IP suite. Attackers focused on overwhelming the network bandwidth of election offices or state government websites by sending a massive volume of traffic that exceeded the capacity of the target's internet connection. A common method was the ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) flood, also known as the 'Ping flood,' where attackers sent a barrage of echo-request packets to the target, forcing the system to respond and eventually exhaust its outgoing bandwidth. Another prevalent method was the SYN flood, which exploited the three-way handshake of the TCP protocol. By sending numerous SYN requests with spoofed IP addresses and never responding to the server's SYN-ACK, the attacker would leave the server’s connection queues full of 'half-open' connections, effectively locking out legitimate voters or officials from accessing election resources. These attacks were relatively unsophisticated, relying on raw power rather than surgical precision, and were often 'noisy,' making them easy for rudimentary intrusion detection systems to identify, though not necessarily easy to stop given the lack of robust cloud-based scrubbing services at the time.",
